<paragraph blockId="37.[151,1437,1454,2019]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">
<emphasis box="[199,323,1454,1479]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Ambulacra</emphasis>
—Petaloid area 61–74% TL, petaloid width 42–51% TL; petals short, with 4–7 pore pairs in each series of petal III and posterior paired petals, 3–5 pore pairs in each series of anterior paired petals; pores small rounded, petals broad, open distally; pore series slightly diverging; interporiferous zones smaller than poriferous zones.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="37.[151,1437,1454,2019]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">
<emphasis box="[199,313,1599,1622]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Peristome</emphasis>
—Moderate in size, diameter 17–21% TL; rounded pentagonal, width 12–17% TL, situated slightly anterior of centre, 37–42% TL from anterior margin of test.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="37.[151,1437,1454,2019]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">
<emphasis box="[199,305,1671,1694]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Periproct</emphasis>
—Small, 9–13% TL; squarish in outline; slightly elongate, width, 8–11% TL; situated closer to peristome than posterior edge, 17–26% TL from posterior margin of test.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="37.[151,1437,1454,2019]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,427,1742,1767]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Geographic range.</emphasis>
Indo-West Pacific, from the Red Sea (
<bibRefCitation author="Clark, H. L." box="[898,1046,1742,1767]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" refId="ref34415" refString="Clark, H. L. (1925 a) A Catalogue of the Recent Sea-Urchins (Echinoidea) in the Collection of the British Museum (Natural History). Oxford University Press, London, 250 pp." type="book" year="1925">Clark 1925a</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Mortensen, T." box="[1063,1265,1743,1767]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" pagination="1 - 15" refId="ref35426" refString="Mortensen, T. (1948 c) Report on the Echinoidea of the Murray Expedition. II [Irregular Echinoidea]. Scientific Reports on the John Murray Expedition, 9, 1 - 15." type="journal article" year="1948">Mortensen 1948c</bibRefCitation>
) to Coral Sea (
<bibRefCitation author="Miskelly, A." box="[158,325,1778,1803]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" refId="ref35198" refString="Miskelly, A. (2002) Sea urchins of Australia and the Indo-Pacific. Capricornica Publications, Lindfield, 179 pp." type="book" year="2002">Miskelly 2002</bibRefCitation>
) and the 
<collectingCountry box="[428,554,1778,1803]" name="Philippines" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Philippines</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Mortensen, T." box="[568,771,1778,1803]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" refId="ref35386" refString="Mortensen, T. (1948 b) A Monograph of the Echinoidea IV. 2. Clypeasteroida. Clypeasteridae, Arachnoidae, Fibulariidae, Laganidae and Scutellidae. C. A. Reitzel, Copenhagen, 471 pp." type="book" year="1948">Mortensen 1948b</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="37.[151,1437,1454,2019]" box="[199,937,1814,1839]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,430,1814,1839]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Bathymetric range.</emphasis>
Intertidal zone to 
<quantity box="[636,707,1814,1839]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.85" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" unit="m" value="385.0">385 m</quantity>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Mortensen, T." box="[721,924,1814,1839]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" refId="ref35386" refString="Mortensen, T. (1948 b) A Monograph of the Echinoidea IV. 2. Clypeasteroida. Clypeasteridae, Arachnoidae, Fibulariidae, Laganidae and Scutellidae. C. A. Reitzel, Copenhagen, 471 pp." type="book" year="1948">Mortensen 1948b</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="37.[151,1437,1454,2019]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,618,1850,1875]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">
Observed occurrence in 
<collectingCountry box="[491,614,1850,1875]" name="Sri Lanka" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Sri Lanka</collectingCountry>
.
</emphasis>
Denuded tests only were found on the beach of Hiriketiya Bay, southern coast of Sri Lanka (
<figureCitation box="[371,455,1886,1911]" captionStart="FIGURE 27" captionStartId="35.[151,250,1877,1899]" captionTargetBox="[187,1426,224,1832]" captionTargetId="figure@35.[151,1436,193,1856]" captionTargetPageId="35" captionText="FIGURE 27. Distribution map of Echinocyamus megapetalus, Fibularia ovulum and Fibularia sp. recorded in this study." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2617513/files/figure.png" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Fig. 27</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="37" pageNumber="38" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="37.[151,1437,1454,2019]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1922,1947]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Remarks</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[325,525,1922,1947]" class="Echinoidea" family="Fibulariidae" genus="Fibularia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Clypeasteroida" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="ovulum">
<emphasis box="[325,525,1922,1947]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Fibularia ovulum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lamarck" authorityYear="1816" box="[683,791,1922,1947]" class="Echinoidea" family="Fibulariidae" genus="Fibularia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Clypeasteroida" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[683,791,1922,1947]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Fibularia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. in having a higher test (
<figureCitation box="[1123,1210,1922,1947]" captionStart="FIGURE 30" captionStartId="37.[151,250,1393,1415]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,938,1371]" captionTargetId="figure@37.[151,1436,938,1371]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="FIGURE 30. Comparison of test height of Fibularia ovulum (A, WUSL/EI/178) and Fibularia sp. (B, WUSL/EI/164)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2617517/files/figure.png" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Fig. 30</figureCitation>
). Test height of Sri Lankan 
<taxonomicName box="[242,440,1958,1983]" class="Echinoidea" family="Fibulariidae" genus="Fibularia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Clypeasteroida" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="ovulum">
<emphasis box="[242,440,1958,1983]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Fibularia ovulum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is relatively low compared to specimens from the 
<collectingCountry box="[1012,1120,1958,1983]" name="Maldives" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Maldives</collectingCountry>
. However, the total petaloid pore pair number overlaps with that of with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lamarck" authorityYear="1816" box="[645,752,1994,2019]" class="Echinoidea" family="Fibulariidae" genus="Fibularia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Clypeasteroida" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[645,752,1994,2019]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Fibularia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. (
<figureCitation box="[807,890,1994,2019]" captionStart="FIGURE 31" captionStartId="38.[151,250,894,916]" captionTargetBox="[281,1274,233,838]" captionTargetId="figure@38.[214,1366,213,860]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURE 31. Scatter plot of total pore pairs vs. test length for the material attributed to Fibularia ovulum (n=8) and Fibularia sp. (n=11)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2617519/files/figure.png" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Fig. 31</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
